The problem can be solved using a modified version of the 0-1 Knapsack problem. We will represent the problem as follows:

We have N ID cards and M gates.
We can pass the i-th gate if we have one of the following ID cards: the L_i-th, (L_i+1)-th,..., and R_i-th ID cards.

We will try to find the maximum number of cards that can be used in each gate without violating the constraint that each gate can be passed only by using one ID card.

Let dp[i][j] be the maximum number of ID cards that can be used in the i-th gate without violating the constraint that we can pass only by using the j-th card.

We can fill the table dp using the following recurrence relation:

dp[i][j] = max(dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j]) if i <= L_i <= R_i and j >= L_i and j <= R_i
dp[i][j] = 0 if i > R_i or j > R_i

We will fill the table dp using dynamic programming approach.

Time Complexity: O(N * M)
Space Complexity: O(N * M)

assert solution("20 12 6") == "12"

The function `solution` takes the input as a string which contains 3 integers separated by spaces. We first split the string by spaces using the `split()` method and convert the resulting list to a tuple. We then unpack the tuple into three variables using the `*` operator.

The function then calculates the number of minutes it takes to make N takoyaki, using the formula:

minutes = N * (T + X - 1)

To calculate the number of takoyaki needed in each minute, we subtract 1 from the total time. This ensures that we always make at least one takoyaki piece in each minute. We then divide the number of minutes by the total time to get the number of takoyaki pieces needed per minute.

Finally, we multiply the number of takoyaki pieces needed per minute by the total time and print the result.

The function returns the string "12" as the output, since we can make 20 takoyaki in 12 minutes.

    else:

The function first checks if the length of the input string is within the valid range. If not, it returns an error message.

Next, the function iterates through each card label and checks if the label is in the correct format. If the label is in the correct format, the function extracts the suit and number from the label. The function then checks if the number is between $1$ and $13$. If the number is not, the function returns an error message.

Finally, if all the checks pass, the function iterates through the deck of poker cards and checks if each card has been labeled. If all cards have been labeled, the function returns the number of missing cards for each suit as a space-separated string. If there are two exact same cards in the deck, the function returns the message "GRESKA".
